[Enter feedback here]

Symptom:
Trying to experiment Azure AD pass-through credential to access ADLS Gen 2.0
Folloing doc: https://docs.microsoft.com/en-gb/azure/databricks/security/credential-passthrough/adls-passthrough

User configured in cluster creation and run the notebook are both my own AD account.
I'm able to upload/download the data to ADLS container using azcopy, and have blob contributor role assigned.
But getting error
AbfsRestOperationException: Operation failed: 'This request is not authorized to perform this operation.', 403, HEAD, https://aubdfpoc.dfs.core.windows.net/test/?upn=false&action=getAccessControl&timeout=90

Solution:
I figured out the reason why it wasnt working initially.

Its working for me now, and please help me close this ticket.
In the meantime, let me explain what happened, and I think the official doc can be enhanced on that.

In my ADLS network settings, I didnt open the access to all networks, but only selected networks, while databricks worker subnet/vnet is not in the list. After adding that to the list, it worked.
The issue Id see as for the doc, error 403 usually indicating authentication or authorisation issues. For networking or firewall issue, a connection timeout error is mot common. And it would immediately help me understand the issue is with networking on storage account.
Also if databricks deployment is by default, the worker vnet is in lock, and wont be able to get added to selected vnets of storage account, as itd require vnet endpoints created.

I think it can be easily missed in the configuration to use the AD credential passthrough. In this case, doc it explicitly or add to FAQ would definitely help the community.

Although the suggestion here help, the actual url that you can find in Ambari / Services / Hive / Summary is not correct. The zookeeper addresses in that URL are incorrect.

What works is copy the url that is suggested there, but replace the three zookeeper addresses by the ones that you can find in each of the components of Ambari / Services / SooKeeper / Summary.

Carefully copying these across to the JDBC configuration Hive URL works
